Dear Shri Narasimha Ji,

Namasthe

 

1.       I deeply appreciate and feel grateful for having shared your
understandings. I would kindly request you to permit me to share my
understandings which stand in definite contrast with that of yours. I would
also request your noble self to allow me to point out a number of flaws,
which I consider as a liberty bestowed on debating scholars. Of course, we
don't become great if we are "scholars" because a scholar is essentially a
person who continues to learn without a pause. I would view this as an
opportunity to rectify our understandings.

 

2.       First of all you quoted Swami Vivekananda as a stamping authority
to support/strengthen your argument. Let me tell you that truth/clarity does
not need any support, because it stands itself as a support for all.(In
Hindi, "satya ko pramaan ki aavashyakta nahi hai, satya swayam apna pramaan
hai")

 

3.       Secondly, if what you have quoted from Swami Vivekananda is true,
then I am skeptical about Swami Vivekananda's understandings himself. Let me
tell you that divinity of soul is ever-existing like Sun (Sadaa Jaagati
Jyoti)(ever shining light). So do you need any effort to manifest it? Do you
mean to say that the ever-shining Brahman is at the mercy of our efforts to
get itself manifested? Perhaps..But let us ponder what actually caused that
sunlight to be eclipsed? Let me tell you that the very idea of considering
that divinity to be eclipsed is ignorance; and consequently trying to make
an effort to remove that eclipse, is a greater ignorance. Any act done under
ignorance will yield only further bondage and eclipse, and trap the soul
into the chakravyuha(tornado) of the maaya.

 

4.       The key idea here is that when we start with an assumption which
itself is faulty, then our whole calculation based on that assumption goes
faulty. So there is no point in proceeding further beyond this, or else it
is just a waste of time, without true/clarity of vision dawning on us.

 

5.       I would humbly request your noble self to view it as a healthy
scholarly debate, which necessitates being blunt and straightforward,
without being circumbulatory. This will be in the general interest and
welfare of all the earnest seekers.

 

6.       I humbly request your noble self to peruse my understandings, and
bless us with further insights.

 

Thanks and Warm Regards,

Kannan

 

