Namaste friends,
 
I am cc'ing this to vedic-wisdom yahoogroup because of the spiritual
content.
 
I agree with Vishnu ji's comment on a specific point in Maja ji's nice
write-up:
 
> > *Also, one is supposed to choose only one ayana for one lifetime and
> > master it to as perfect as possible. *
> 
>  I am not entirely sure if the above statement is correct. It is very much
> possible and in fact is a measure of self realized people.
 
Indeed, one can carve one's own niche by combining multiple paths. They are
not meant to be mutually exclusive.
 
I'll quote Swami Vivekananda from his book "Raja Yoga" where he makes a
comment on the 4 paths:
 
"Each soul is potentially divine. The goal is to manifest this divinity
within by controlling nature: external and internal. Do this either by work
or worship or psychic control, or philosophy - by one, or more, or all of
these - and be free."
 
Here are my 2 cents.
 
Jnana yoga emphasizes on philosophization and wisdom. Karma yoga emphasizes
on work and detachment. Raja yoga emphasizes on self-control and
self-mastery. Bhakti yoga emphasizes on devotion and surrender to Supreme.
One can pick whatever is natural to one and try to develop that quality.
However, wisdom, detached action, self-control and surrender to the Supreme
are not mutually exclusive. As one of these qualities develops nicely in
one, others will automatically develop too! Finally, a realized person (i.e.
one in "Yoga" or oneness) will have all these qualities fully blossomed.
 
Forget about horoscope, navamsa, vimsamsa, nakshatramsa etc. Irrespective of
that, I strongly recommend against Raja yoga for 99% of humanity. Even
Ramakrishna advised against it. Controlling body and mind and forcing the
psychic life force to purify and ascend requires strict yama and niyama and
clean nadis. In this age of polluted air, water and food, nadis accumulate
great amounts of obstructions and Raja yoga can be dangerous. This is not
just my view, but what Ramakrishna explicitly taught in "Gospel of
Ramakrishna" (one of the greatest spiritual texts IMHO). He discouraged
several of his sishyas from pursuing Raja Yoga. He taught it to Vivekananda,
but did not encourage even him to practice it.
 
Jnana yoga is brilliant, but there is a distinct danger of falling into the
delusional trap of pseudo-wisdom. People of this age are not
sincere/honest/smart enough for it. It is easy to delude that "all is
Brahman. I am Brahman. Whatever I do, it's ok - it doesn't matter. It's all
a delusion anyway" without fully overcoming all innate conditioning that
reinforces duality in consciousness every instant. Kind of like declaring
wisely in a movie that "it's just a movie and not reality", but flinching in
every scary scene, crying in every sad scene etc. Without absolute honesty,
sincerely and earnestness, jnana yoga can be problematic too. A long path of
constant contemplation and self-correction can be reduced to a quick
delusional jump to the end.
 
IMHo, for most people in this age, Bhakti yoga and Karma yoga are the most
suitable and safest.
 
Best regards,
Narasimha
